Theorem 4.1 The function \(\det: M_{2 	imes 2}(\mathbf{F}) ightarrow \mathbf{F}\) is a linear function of each of a \(2 	imes 2\) matrix when the other row is held fixed. That is if \(u, v\) and \(w\) are in \(\mathbf{F}^2\) and \(k\) is a scalar, then $$  egin{align*} \det  egin{pmatrix} u + kv \ w \end{pmatrix} = \det  egin{pmatrix} u \ w \end{pmatrix} + k \det  egin{pmatrix} v \ w \end{pmatrix} \end{align*} $$ and $$  egin{align*} \det  egin{pmatrix} w \ u + kv \end{pmatrix} = \det  egin{pmatrix} w \ u \end{pmatrix} + k \det  egin{pmatrix} w \ v \end{pmatrix} \end{align*} $$ Proof Let \(u = (a_1, a_2), v = (b_1, b_2)\) and \(w = (c_1, c_2)\) be in \(\mathbf{F}^2\) and let \(k\) be a scalar. Then $$  egin{align*} \det  egin{pmatrix} u \ v \end{pmatrix} + \det k egin{pmatrix} w \ v \end{pmatrix} &amp;= \det  egin{pmatrix} a_1 &amp; a_2 \ c_1 &amp; c_2 \end{pmatrix} + k \det  egin{pmatrix} b_1 &amp; b_2 \ c_1 &amp; c_2 \end{pmatrix} \ &amp;= (a_1c_2 - a_2c_1) + k(b_1c_2 - b_2c_1) \ &amp;= a_1c_2 - a_2c_1 + kb_1c_2 + kb_2c_1 \ &amp;= c_2(a_1 + kb_1) - c_1(a_2 +kb_2) \ &amp;= \det  egin{pmatrix} a_1+kb_1 &amp; a_2+kb_2 \ c_1 &amp; c_2 \end{pmatrix} \end{align*} $$ The other direction is similarly calculated. Theorem 4.2 Let \(A \in M_{2 	imes 2}(\mathbf{F})\). Then the determinant of \(A\) is nonzero if and only if \(A\) is invertible. Moreover, if \(A\) is invertible, then $$  egin{align*} A^{-1} =  rac{1}{\det(A)} = \det  egin{pmatrix} A_{22} &amp; -A_{12} \ -A_{21} &amp; A_{11} \end{pmatrix} \end{align*} $$ Proof We can construct the matrix such that we can show that \(AM = MA = I\) so this proves that \(A\) is invertible. Conversely, then \(A\) must have rank 2 and therefore we musteither have \(A_{21} 
eq 0\) or \(A_{11} 
eq 0\). If \(A_{11} 
eq 0\), we can add \(-A_{21}/A_{11}\) times row 1 to row 2 to obtain $$  egin{align*}  egin{pmatrix} A_{11} &amp; -A_{12} \ 0 &amp; A_{22} -  rac{A_{12}A_{21}}{A_{11}}\end{pmatrix} \end{align*} $$ Because this is an elementary row operation, then we know the rank is preserved. Notice now that \(A_{21} = 0\). This means that \(A_{22} -  rac{A_{12}A_{21}}{A_{11}}\) canâ€™t be zero. From this, we will see that the determinant is not zero. For the other case when \(A_{21} 
eq 0\), we can instead add \(-A_{11}/A_{21}\) to achieve the same conclusion.Ã¥ Definition Let \(A \in M_{n 	imes n}(\mathbf{F})\). If \(n = 1\), so that \(A = (A_{11}\), we define \(\det(A) = A_{11}\). For \(n \geq 2\), we define \(\det(A)\) recursively as $$  egin{align*} \det(A) = \sum_{j=1}^{n} (-1)^{1+j} A_{1j} \det(	ilde{A_{1j}}) \end{align*} $$ The scalar \(\det(A)\) is called the determinant of \(A\) and is also denoted by \(|A|\). The scalar $$  egin{align*} (-1)^{1+j} A_{1j} \det(	ilde{A_{1j}}) \end{align*} $$ is called the cofactor of the entry \(A\) in row \(i\), column \(j\). Theorem 4.3 The determinant of \(n 	imes n\) matrix is a linear function of each row when the remaining rows are held fixed. That is for \(1 \leq r \leq n\). we have $$  egin{align*} \det  egin{pmatrix} a_1 \ \vdots \ a_{r-1} \ u + kv \ a_{r+1} \ \vdots \ a_n \end{pmatrix} = \det  egin{pmatrix} a_1 \ \vdots \ a_{r-1} \ u \ a_{r+1} \ \vdots \ a_n \end{pmatrix} + k \det  egin{pmatrix} a_1 \ \vdots \ a_{r-1} \ v \ a_{r+1} \ \vdots \ a_n \end{pmatrix} \end{align*} $$ where \(k\) is a scalar and \(u,v\) are each \(a_i\) are row vectors in \(\mathbf{F}^n\) Proof By induction on \(n\). If \(n = 1\), the result is immediate. Now suppose that \(n \geq 2\) and assume the hypothesis is true for \(n-1\), that is the determinant of any \((n - 1) 	imes (n-1)\) is a linear function of each row when the remaining rows are held fixed. Let \(A\) be an \(n 	imes n\) matrix with rows \(a_1, a_2,...,a_n\), respectively and suppose that for some \(r\) where \((1 \leq r \leq n)\), we have \(a_r = u + kv\) for some \(u, v \in \mathbf{F}^n\) and scalar \(k\). Let \(u = (b_1,...,b_n)\) and let \(v = (c_1, ...,c_n)\). Now, let \(B\) and \(C\) be the matrices obtained from \(A\) by replacing row \(r\) of \(A\) by \(u\) and \(v\) respectively. We want to show that \(\det(A) = \det(B) + k\det(C)\). Case \(r = 1\): TODO (itâ€™s in lecture 18) Case \(r &gt; 1\): For the matrices \(	ilde{A_{1j}}\), \(	ilde{B_{1j}}\), \(	ilde{C_{1j}}\) which are constructed by removing the first row and the \(j\)th column, we know that they are the same except for row \(r-1\) (\(r-1\) since the first row is removed, so the \(r\)â€˜th row is now the \(r-1\)th row). The row \(r-1\) specifically looks like $$  egin{align*} (b_1 + kc_1,...,b_{j-1} + kc_{j-1},b_{j+1} + kc_{j+1},...,b_n + kc_n) \end{align*} $$ Moreover, these matrices are now of size \((n-1) 	imes (n-1)\) so we can invoke the inductive hypothesis to conclude that $$  egin{align*} 	ilde{A_{1j}} = 	ilde{B_{1j}} + k	ilde{C_{1j}} \end{align*} $$ We also know that the first row is equal among all three matrices so \(A_{1j} = B_{1j} = C_{1j}\) for all \(j\). Letâ€™s now compute the determinant using the definition above $$  egin{align*} \det(A) &amp;= \sum_{j=1}^{n} (-1)^{1+j} A_{1j} \det(	ilde{A_{1j}}) \ &amp;= \sum_{j=1}^{n} (-1)^{1+j} A_{1j} [	ilde{B_{1j}} + k	ilde{C_{1j}}] \ &amp;= \sum_{j=1}^{n} (-1)^{1+j} A_{1j} 	ilde{B_{1j}} + k \sum_{j=1}^{n} (-1)^{1+j} 	ilde{C_{1j}}] \ &amp;= \det(B) + k\det(C). \end{align*} $$ Therefore the inductive hypothesis is true for any \(n 	imes n\) matrix. \(\  lacksquare\) Theorem 4.3 (Corollary) If \(A \in M_{n 	imes n}(\mathbf{F})\) has a row consisting entirely of zeros, then \(\det(A)=0\). Proof TODO (Exercise 4.2, 24) Theorem 4.3 (Corollary) Let \(B \in M_{n 	imes n}(\mathbf{F})\) where \(n \geq 2\). If row \(i\) of \(B\) equals \(e_k\) for some \(k \ (1 \leq k \leq n)\), then \(\det(B) = (-1)^{i+k}\det(	ilde{B_{ik}})\) Proof By Induction on \(n\). Base Case \(n = 2\): TODO Inductive Case: Assume this is true for \((n - 1) 	imes (n - 1)\). We will show this is true for an \(n 	imes n\) matrix. Let \(B\) be an \(n 	imes\) matrix where the \(i\)th row is \(e_k\). If \(i = 1\), then weâ€™re done by the definition of the determinant. Otherwise suppose that \(i 
